Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with
a large drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @Southwest Spice Blend{1%teaspoon},
@salt{pinch}, and @pepper{pinch}. (You'll use the rest of the Southwest
Spice Blend later.)

Roast on top rack until lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While potatoes roast, halve, peel, and very thinly slice ¼ of the @red onion{1};
finely chop remaining. Quarter @lime{1}. Halve @brioche buns{2}.

In a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, combine sliced onion, juice from half the
lime, @sugar{1/4%teaspoon}, and a pinch of salt. Microwave until onion is
softened, ~{1%minute}. Set aside.

== Sauce Base ==

In a #second small bowl{}, combine @mushroom stock concentrate{1},
@cornstarch{1/2%tablespoon}, remaining @Southwest Spice Blend{1/2%tablespoon},
and @water{1%tablespoon}.

In a #third small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} and a squeeze of
lime juice. Season with salt.

== Plant-Based Protein Filling ==

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chopped onion;
cook, stirring, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add @Tex-Mex ground plant-based protein{8%ounce}; season with salt and pepper.
Using a #spatula{}, press into an even layer; cook, undisturbed, until browned
on bottom, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Break up protein into pieces and continue cooking until browned and warmed
through, ~{3-4%minutes} more.

== Finishing ==

Add @water{2%tablespoon} to pan with plant-based protein, then stir in sauce
base. Cook, stirring, until sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. (If sauce seems
too thick, add another splash of water.) Taste and season with salt and pepper.
Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, toast buns until golden brown.

== Assembly ==

Divide buns between plates; spread cut sides of bottom buns with lime mayo.
Fill buns with messy jane filling and as much pickled onion (draining first) as
you like. Serve with potato wedges on the side and any remaining lime mayo for
dipping.

> Ground Plant-Based Protein is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.